#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:10
msgid "2.2 Recurrent Networks and Content-Addressable Memory"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:12
msgid ""
"The perceptron exemplifies <b>feedforward</b> computation: information "
"flows unidirectionally from input to output, and the network's state is "
"entirely determined by the current input. This architecture is well-"
"suited for pattern classification and function approximation, but it is "
"fundamentally incapable of modeling temporal dependencies or exhibiting "
"persistent internal states. To understand the architectural lineage that "
"culminates in the Boltzmann machine, we must introduce <b>recurrent "
"neural networks, </b>networks in which connections form directed cycles, "
"allowing information to persist and dynamics to unfold over time. This "
"section focuses on the recurrent architecture that directly precedes the "
"Boltzmann machine, while the previous section 2.1 established the "
"fundamental limitations of simple feedforward networks."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:15
msgid "<b>From Feedforward to Recurrence</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:17
msgid ""
"A recurrent neural network (RNN) differs from a feedforward network in a "
"single, crucial respect: at least some of its connections form "
"<b>feedback loops</b>. The output of a neuron at one time step can "
"influence its own input, or the input of neurons earlier in the "
"processing chain at subsequent time steps. This architectural difference "
"has profound consequences:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:19
msgid ""
"<b>State persistence</b>: The network maintains an internal state that "
"evolves over time, enabling it to process sequences of inputs or to "
"settle into stable patterns even in the absence of external input."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:20
msgid ""
"<b>Dynamical systems</b>: An RNN is best understood not as a static "
"function approximator but as a <b>dynamical system</b> whose state "
"trajectory is governed by its weights and the initial conditions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:21
msgid ""
"<b>Memory</b>: Recurrence provides a form of <b>short-term memory</b> "
"that extends beyond the single feedforward pass."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:23
msgid "<b>The Hopfield Network: A Prototypical Recurrent Architecture</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:25
msgid ""
"The <b>Hopfield network</b>, introduced by John Hopfield in 1982, is the "
"canonical example of a recurrent network designed for <b>associative "
"memory</b>. Its elegant formulation and deep connection to statistical "
"physics make it the direct conceptual precursor to the Boltzmann machine."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:27
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"A Hopfield network consists of $N$ binary units, each taking values in "
"$\\{-1, +1\\}$ (or equivalently $\\{0, 1\\}$). Every unit is connected to"
" every other unit, forming a <b>fully connected recurrent graph</b>. The "
"connections are <b>symmetric</b>:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:29
#, python-brace-format
msgid "w_{ij} = w_{ji},\\quad \\forall i, j"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:31
#, python-brace-format
msgid "and there are no self-connections: $w_{ii} = 0$."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:33
msgid ""
"The network operates in discrete time. At each time step, a single unit "
"is selected at random (or according to a fixed schedule) and its state is"
" updated according to a deterministic rule:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:35
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"x_i \\leftarrow \\text{sign}\\left( \\sum_{j \\neq i} w_{ij} x_j + b_i "
"\\right)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:37
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"This <b>asynchronous update</b> dynamics continues until the network "
"reaches a <b>fixed point, </b>a state $\\mathbf{x}$ that remains "
"unchanged under the update rule. The symmetry of the weight matrix "
"guarantees that such fixed points exist and that the dynamics will "
"converge to one from any initial state"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:39
msgid "<b>Energy Landscape and Convergence</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:41
msgid ""
"The convergence of the Hopfield network is guaranteed by the existence of"
" a <b>Lyapunov function</b> (or energy function) that decreases "
"monotonically with each state update. For the Hopfield network, this "
"energy is defined as:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:43
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"E(\\mathbf{x}) = -\\frac{1}{2} \\sum_{i \\neq j} w_{ij} x_i x_j - \\sum_i"
" b_i x_i"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:45
msgid "or, in matrix form:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:47
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"E(\\mathbf{x}) = -\\frac{1}{2} \\mathbf{x}^\\top \\mathbf{W} \\mathbf{x} "
"- \\mathbf{b}^\\top \\mathbf{x}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:49
msgid ""
"To verify that energy never increases, consider a flip of unit $i$from "
"$x_i$ to $x_i' = -x_i$. The change in energy is:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:51
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"\\Delta E = E(\\mathbf{x}') - E(\\mathbf{x}) = (x_i - x_i')\\left( "
"\\sum_{j \\neq i} w_{ij} x_j + b_i \\right)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:53
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"If $x_i'$ is chosen to be $ \\text{sign}(\\sum w_{ij} x_j + b_i)$, then "
"the term in parentheses has the same sign as $x_i'$. Since $x_i$ has the "
"opposite sign, the product $(x_i - x_i')$ is non-zero and opposite in "
"sign to the parenthesized term, ensuring $\\Delta E \\leq 0$. Energy "
"strictly decreases unless the unit is already aligned with its input."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:55
msgid ""
"Because the energy is bounded below (for finite weights and binary "
"units), the network must eventually reach a <b>local minimum</b> of the "
"energy function, where no single-unit flip can further lower the energy. "
"These local minima are the <b>attractors</b> of the dynamic, which states"
" toward which nearby initial configurations evolve."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:57
msgid "<b>Storing Memories as Attractors</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:59
msgid ""
"The Hopfield network is not merely a dynamical curiosity; it is a model "
"of <b>content-addressable memory</b>. The goal is to store a set of "
"desired patterns $\\{\\boldsymbol{\\xi}^1, \\boldsymbol{\\xi}^2, \\ldots,"
" \\boldsymbol{\\xi}^P\\}$ as attractors of network dynamics. When "
"presented with a corrupted or partial version of a stored pattern as the "
"initial state, the network's deterministic descent down the energy "
"landscape will restore the complete, original memory."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:61
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"The <b>Hebbian learning rule</b> provides a biologically inspired "
"prescription for setting weights. For binary $ \\{-1, +1\\}$patterns, the"
" weight between units $i$ and $j$ is set to:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:63
#, python-brace-format
msgid "w_{ij} = \\frac{1}{N} \\sum_{\\mu=1}^P \\xi_i^\\mu \\xi_j^\\mu"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:65
msgid ""
"This rule is local, incremental, and plausible as a synaptic plasticity "
"mechanism. Each stored pattern contributes $+1/N$ if units $i$ and $j$ "
"have the same sign in that pattern, and $-1/N$ if they differ. The "
"weights thus reflect the average correlation between units across the set"
" of memories."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:67
msgid "<b>Retrieval Dynamics: Pattern Completion and Error Correction</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:69
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"Consider a stored pattern $\\boldsymbol{\\xi}^\\mu$. Under the Hebbian "
"weight matrix, the input to unit $i$ when the network is in state "
"$\\boldsymbol{\\xi}^\\mu$ is:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:71
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"\\sum_{j \\neq i} w_{ij} \\xi_j^\\mu = \\frac{1}{N} \\sum_{j \\neq i} "
"\\sum_{\\nu=1}^P \\xi_i^\\nu \\xi_j^\\nu \\xi_j^\\mu"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:73
msgid ""
"This sum decomposes into a <b>signal</b> term (when $\\nu = \\mu$) and a "
"<b>noise</b> or <b>crosstalk</b> term (when $\\nu \\neq \\mu$):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:75
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"\\text{Signal} = \\frac{1}{N} \\sum_{j \\neq i} \\xi_i^\\mu "
"(\\xi_j^\\mu)^2 = \\frac{N-1}{N} \\xi_i^\\mu \\approx \\xi_i^\\mu"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:77
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"\\text{Noise} = \\frac{1}{N} \\sum_{\\nu \\neq \\mu} \\sum_{j \\neq i} "
"\\xi_i^\\nu \\xi_j^\\nu \\xi_j^\\mu"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:79
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"If the stored patterns are random and uncorrelated, the noise term is "
"approximately Gaussian with zero mean and variance proportional to $P/N$."
" As long as the number of stored patterns $P$ is small compared to $N$, "
"the signal dominates, and the pattern $\\boldsymbol{\\xi}^\\mu$ is a "
"stable fixed point."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:81
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"When the initial state is a <b>corrupted </b>version of "
"$\\boldsymbol{\\xi}^\\mu$, say, with a fraction of bits flipped, the "
"network dynamics drive the state back toward the original pattern. Each "
"unit \"votes\" according to its connections, and the collective influence"
" of the correctly recalled bits overwhelms the errors. This is <b>pattern"
" completion</b>: the network fills in missing or noisy information by "
"descending the energy landscape toward the nearest memory attractor."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:83
msgid "<b>Content-Addressable vs. Address-Based Memory</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:85
msgid ""
"Conventional computer memory is <b>address-based</b>: to retrieve an "
"item, you must supply its exact memory address (or a pointer to it). If "
"the address is corrupted or unknown, retrieval is impossible. Content-"
"addressable memory, in contrast, allows retrieval based on <b>partial or "
"approximate content</b>. You provide a fragment of the desired memory, "
"and the system returns the complete item that best matches the fragment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:87
msgid ""
"The Hopfield network implements content-addressable memory in a "
"distributed, fault-tolerant manner:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:89
msgid ""
"<b>Distributed representation</b>: Each memory is stored across many "
"synaptic weights, and each weight contributes to the storage of many "
"memories."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:90
msgid ""
"<b>Graceful degradation</b>: As more memories are stored, retrieval "
"becomes noisier but does not fail catastrophically until a critical "
"capacity is exceeded."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:91
msgid ""
"<b>Parallel processing</b>: All units update concurrently, allowing fast "
"retrieval times that are independent of the number of stored memories."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:93
msgid "<b>Capacity Limitations and Spurious Attractors</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:95
msgid ""
"The Hopfield network's capacity is not infinite. As the number of stored "
"patterns $P$ increases, the crosstalk noise grows. Beyond a critical "
"<b>storage capacity</b> of approximately $ \\alpha_c \\approx 0.14 N$ "
"(for random, unbiased patterns), the memories are no longer stable. The "
"network undergoes a phase transition in which the intended attractors "
"merge or disappear, and retrieval error rises abruptly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:97
msgid ""
"Moreover, the Hebbian learning rule creates <b>spurious attractors, "
"</b>stable states that do not correspond to any stored memory. These "
"arise from:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:99
msgid ""
"<b>Mixture states</b>: Linear combinations of an odd number of stored "
"patterns."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:100
msgid ""
"<b>Spin-reversed states</b>: The global negation of any stored pattern is"
" also an attractor."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:101
msgid ""
"<b>Random valleys</b>: Intrinsic local minima of the disordered energy "
"landscape."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:103
msgid ""
"These spurious attractors are the price of distributed, content-"
"addressable storage. They limit the practical capacity of the network and"
" can trap dynamics in unintended states."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:105
msgid "<b>From Hopfield to Boltzmann: The Missing Ingredient</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:107
msgid ""
"The Hopfield network demonstrates that recurrent, symmetric networks can "
"function as powerful associative memories. Yet it suffers from a critical"
" limitation as a <b>generative model</b> of data: its dynamics are "
"strictly deterministic and converge to the <em>nearest</em> local "
"minimum, regardless of whether that minimum is a true memory, a spurious "
"attractor, or merely a shallow basin in the energy landscape."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:109
msgid ""
"The <b>Boltzmann machine</b> addresses this limitation by introducing "
"<b>stochasticity</b> into the state updates, as previewed in Section [1.3"
" The Need for Noise: Escaping Spurious Minima](/kpp-theoretical-"
"foundations\\kpp-theoretical-foundations-stat-noise). Instead of "
"deterministic thresholding, units update according to a probabilistic "
"rule:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:111
msgid "P(x_i = 1) = \\sigma\\left( \\frac{\\sum_j w_{ij} x_j + b_i}{T} \\right)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:113
msgid ""
"This single modification transforms the Hopfield network from a "
"deterministic content-addressable memory into a <b>probabilistic "
"generative model</b> capable of:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:115
msgid ""
"<b>Sampling from a distribution</b>: The network no longer converges to a"
" single fixed point but generates samples from the equilibrium Boltzmann "
"distribution."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:116
msgid ""
"<b>Exploring multiple modes</b>: Thermal noise allows the network to "
"visit different attractor basins, capturing the multimodal structure of "
"complex data."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:117
msgid ""
"<b>Learning by maximum likelihood</b>: The probabilistic formulation "
"provides a principled objective function (maximizing the likelihood of "
"observed data) and a learning algorithm based on contrasting clamped and "
"free-running statistics."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:119
msgid ""
"Effectively, the Boltzmann machine allows the system to sample from a "
"canonical ensemble (see Section [1.2 The Boltzmann Distribution and "
"Equilibrium](/kpp-theoretical-foundations\\kpp-theoretical-foundations-"
"stat-boltzmann)) rather than simply descending into the nearest "
"deterministic fixed point."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:121
msgid ""
"The connection is profound: the Hopfield network defines the <b>energy "
"landscape</b>, while the Boltzmann machine defines the <b>probability "
"distribution</b> over that landscape. The two are intimately related by "
"the Boltzmann distribution:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:123
#, python-brace-format
msgid "P(\\mathbf{x}) = \\frac{1}{Z} \\exp\\left(-E(\\mathbf{x}) / T\\right)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:125
msgid ""
"As $T \\to 0$, the Boltzmann machine reduces to the deterministic "
"Hopfield network. At finite temperatures, it becomes a flexible, "
"probabilistic model of data."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:127
msgid "<b>Summary</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:129
msgid ""
"<b>Recurrent neural networks</b> introduce feedback loops, enabling "
"persistent internal states and dynamical behavior over time."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:130
msgid ""
"The <b>Hopfield network</b> is a fully connected recurrent network with "
"symmetric weights, designed for <b>content-addressable memory</b>."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:131
msgid ""
"The network's dynamics minimize an <b>energy function</b>, guaranteeing "
"convergence to <b>local minima </b> that serve as attractors for stored "
"memories."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:132
msgid ""
"The <b>Hebbian learning rule</b> stores patterns as correlations in the "
"weight matrix, enabling pattern completion and error correction."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:133
msgid ""
"<b>Spurious attractors</b> and limited <b>storage capacity</b> are "
"intrinsic drawbacks of the Hopfield model."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:134
msgid ""
"The <b>Boltzmann machine</b> extends the Hopfield network by replacing "
"deterministic updates with <b>stochastic sampling</b>, transforming an "
"associative memory into a <b>probabilistic generative model</b>."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recurrent.md:135
msgid ""
"The Hopfield energy function becomes the basis for the <b>Boltzmann "
"distribution</b>, linking deterministic attractor dynamics to "
"probabilistic inference."
msgstr ""

